<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,654,1363]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,385,654,679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Material examined.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2147524706" collectingDate="2014-05-17" collectingDateMax="2014-06-08" collectingDateMin="2014-05-17" collectorName="Dk SJ" country="Denmark" location="DENMARK" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus box="[393,497,654,679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Holotype</typeStatus>
male, 
<collectingCountry box="[575,720,655,679]" name="Denmark" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">DENMARK</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectorName box="[732,803,654,679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Dk SJ</collectorName>
, Draved Skov, Højmose, 
<date box="[1095,1257,654,679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" value="2014-05-17" valueMax="2014-06-08" valueMin="2014-05-17">
<collectingDate box="[1095,1257,654,679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" value="2014-05-17" valueMax="2014-06-08" valueMin="2014-05-17">17.v–8.vi.2014</collectingDate>
</date>
, Esben Bøggild (UCMZ-8-184). Description. Male. Head as 
<figureCitation box="[652,734,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–78" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,208,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 72–78. Megaselia legrandi sp. n. male. 72. head 73. proboscis and palp. 74–76. hypopygium. 77. front tarsus. 78. wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617709/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
, the frons having dense but very fine microtrichia. Cheek with 4 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels, which lack SPS vesicles, and palps as 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 72–78" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,208,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 72–78. Megaselia legrandi sp. n. male. 72. head 73. proboscis and palp. 74–76. hypopygium. 77. front tarsus. 78. wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617709/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
. Thorax brown, with 3 notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron with hairs and a bristle. Scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with moderate hairs only a little longer at rear of T6. Venter gray and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 72–78" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,208,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 72–78. Megaselia legrandi sp. n. male. 72. head 73. proboscis and palp. 74–76. hypopygium. 77. front tarsus. 78. wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617709/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Figs 74–76</figureCitation>
. Legs brown but not dark, the front pair being paler. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation box="[950,1030,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–78" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,208,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 72–78. Megaselia legrandi sp. n. male. 72. head 73. proboscis and palp. 74–76. hypopygium. 77. front tarsus. 78. wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617709/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–5. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.7 times its length. Hind femur with hairs below basal half longer than those of the antero-ventral row of outer half. Hind tibia with a dozen moderately differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[1291,1372,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–78" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,208,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,193,1889]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 72–78. Megaselia legrandi sp. n. male. 72. head 73. proboscis and palp. 74–76. hypopygium. 77. front tarsus. 78. wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2617709/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.60 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.45. Costal ratios 3.56: 1.80: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[1094,1194,1015,1039]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.10 mm</quantity>
long. No hair at base of vein 3. With 2 unequal axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity box="[860,960,1051,1075]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere brown.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,654,1363]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,346,1086,1111]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[505,694,1086,1111]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" refId="ref7421" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica. Part UI. Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 455 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
it runs to Group II couplet 6 lead 1, but it differs from the somewhat similar 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[234,418,1122,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rudis">
<emphasis box="[234,326,1122,1147]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">M. rudis</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
by its darker legs and very pale wings. In the key to British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[1175,1324,1122,1147]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7235" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 57 where the positions of the antial bristles on the left side directs one to couplet 58 lead 2 but those of the right side directs one to couplet 59 lead 2. In both cases the hypopygia are different. However, at couplet 59 lead 2 the hypopygium of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[329,541,1230,1255]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinata">
<emphasis box="[329,448,1231,1254]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">M. spinata</emphasis>
(Wood)
</taxonomicName>
is very similar apart from the hypandria, with the single lobe being on the right side in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[231,350,1268,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinata">
<emphasis box="[231,350,1268,1291]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">M. spinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in the left side in 
<emphasis box="[594,731,1266,1291]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henry &amp; Bøggild" authorityYear="2019" box="[594,727,1266,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="legrandi">M. legrandi</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In addition the legs are paler in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[1091,1209,1268,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinata">
<emphasis box="[1091,1209,1268,1291]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">M. spinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the hind femur being yellow with a brown tip. In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz, H." box="[646,816,1302,1327]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" pagination="417 - 464" refId="ref7494" refString="Schmitz, H. (1957.) Phoridae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region. 4 (33). Lieferung 196. E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 417 - 464." type="book chapter" year="1957">Schmitz (1957)</bibRefCitation>
for Abteilung II it runs to couplet 13 lead 1 to 
<emphasis box="[1324,1424,1302,1327]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1324,1420,1302,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rudis">M. rudis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,912,1338,1363]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,654,1363]" box="[199,912,1338,1363]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1338,1363]" pageId="9" pageNumber="72">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after Edgar Allan Poe’s fabulous naturalist.
